BIB                 12         40
TITLE      Production Cross Section of N16 and N17
AUTHOR     (P.A.Roys,K.Shure)
REFERENCE  (J,NSE,4,536,1958)
           #doi:10.13182/NSE58-A28830
REL-REF    (A,14864001,W.J.Henderson+,J,NSE,3,145,1958)
INSTITUTE  (1USABET)
FACILITY   (REAC,1USAORL) Materials Testing Reactor (MTR).
INC-SPECT  Fission spectrum. Since the fission neutron spectrum
           shows a sharply decreasing number of neutrons with
           increasing energy, it is anticipated that the neutron
           spectral distribution above 8 Mev will be relatively
           unaffected by the moderating properties of the
           region about the thimble. The results indicate that
           over this range the spectral shape is essentially
           described by the Watt fission neutron spectrum. The
           cross section for N16 and N17 weighted with the flux
           spectrum in the thimble has been determined.
SAMPLE     A continuously flowing sample of effluent cooling
           water was obtained from the bottom of an NRX fuel rod
           assembly. The sample passed through a solenoid valve
           and into a flat cylindrical tank fabricated from
           sheet aluminum. The tank and measuring equipment were
           surrounded by steel and masonite shielding blocks to
           reduce the neutron background at the measuring
           equipment and also to provide biological shielding from
            the N16 activity in the water.
METHOD     (ACTIV) N16 and N17 are obtained in the experiment by
           continuously piping fresh demineralized water through
           a long, thin irradiation thimble in the high, fast
           neutron flux region of the Materials Testing Reactor.
           The water is then piped to a flat cylindrical plastic
           source disk located outside the reactor. Gamma rays
           from N16 and neutrons from N17 have been detected.
           From the measurements and the known geometry, the
           cross sections for the 016(n,p)N16 and the 017(n,p)N17
           reactions averaged over the fission neutron spectrum
           have been deduced.
MONITOR    (13-AL-27(N,X)11-NA-24,,SIG)
